## Part 7: Unified Tool & Terminal Logic (New)

### Motivation
Both `DesignTools` (the visual UI buttons) and `DesignTerminal` (the pseudo-CLI) currently execute overlapping actions without a shared source of truth. By linking them through the `PDMTools` constant, any action typed in the prompt can directly map to the backend's allowed toolset.

### 7.1 Single Source of Truth (`constants.ts`)
- **[MODIFY]** `DesignTools` in `functions/src/core/constants.ts`
  - Ensure every tool has a `terminalCommand` property string (e.g. `move`, `rotate`, `sketch`).
  - *Note:* We will use `terminalCommand` strings instead of actual Javascript function pointers `toolFunction` to keep the constants serializable across the network and strictly JSON-compatible for Firebase.

### 7.2 Core Dispatcher (`src/lib/design.ts`)
- **[MODIFY]** `DesignController`
  - Expose a new standard method: `executeToolCommand(toolId: string)`.
  - Migrate the inline `handleToolClick` from `DesignTools.tsx` into this exported method. This allows React components (buttons) and Zustand CLI commands (AST parsers) to fire exactly the same sequence.

### 7.3 `DesignTerminal` Upgrade (`DesignTerminal.tsx`)
- **[MODIFY]** Terminal syntax mapping
  - Change `/help` to `--help`.
  - When `--help` is fired, iterate dynamically through the `PDMTools` mapping tools natively to their descriptions.
  - `#` Operator: Maps autocomplete suggestions and AST parsing strictly to `PDMTools` objects inside the `edit` group.
  - `&` Operator: Introduced specifically to match `add` group tools (e.g., `&sketch`, `&part`). Matches trigger `executeToolCommand(tool.id)`.
